{{coord|39.916667|25.550000|display=title}} [[Image:GR Lemnos.PNG|thumb|right|250px|Location of Lemnos]] '''Chryse''' {{IPAc-en|ˈ|k|r|aɪ|s|i|,_|ˈ|k|r|aɪ|z|i}} ({{lang-el|Χρύση|Khrúsē|Golden}}) was a small island in the [[Aegean Sea]] mentioned by [[Homer]], [[Sophocles]] and [[Pausanias (geographer)|Pausanias]].
The island's main feature was said to be its temple to [[Apollo]], and its patron deity a goddess named [[Chryse (goddess)|Chryse]]. The Greek archer [[Philoctetes]] stopped there on his way to [[Troy]] and was fatally bitten by a [[Viperidae|viper]]. [[Lucullus]] captured three men there in an ambush during the [[Third Mithridatic War]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Gillies|first=John|title=The history of ancient Greece: its colonies and conquests; from the earliest accounts till the division of the Macedonian empire in the East. Including the history of literature, philosophy, and the fine arts, Volume 4, Part 2|publisher=T. Cadell and W. Davies|year=1820|volume=4|page=249|chapter=XXVII: From Alexander to Augustus|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rUAZAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA249&lpg=PA249&dq=Appian%2BChryse+Island&source=bl&ots=IwfUZtIdRo&sig=n1Cn353eNupWb1Mxesh75dJn29Q&hl=en&ei=XIaFSq0mjrW2B_6YpdEJ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=6#v=onepage&q=Appian%2BChryse%20Island&f=false}}</ref> The island seems to have disappeared by the 2nd century AD; it is mentioned by [[Pausanias (geographer)|Pausanias]] <ref>8.33.4</ref> and [[Appian]].<ref>Mithridat. c. 72 ''et seq.''</ref> An ancient oracle (written by [[Onomacritus]]) may have predicted this end.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?hl=es&id=kRrJqFKU6N8C&dq=bakis&q=scapegoat#v=snippet&q=scapegoat&f=false Javier Martínez, "Onomacritus the Forger, Hipparchus' Scapegoat?", in ''Fakes and Forgers of Classical Literature'', Madrid, 2011, p. 225], {{ISBN|84-7882-725-0}}.</ref>
The ''[[Description of Greece]]'' says: {{Quote|The following incident proves the might of Fortune to be greater and more marvellous than is shown by the disasters and prosperity of cities. No long sail from [[Lemnos]] was once an island Chryse, where, it is said, Philoctetes met with his accident from the water-snake. But the waves utterly overwhelmed it, and Chryse sank and disappeared in the depths... So temporary and utterly weak are the fortunes of men.|Pausanias, ''Description of Greece'' 8.33.4}}
An amateur underwater archaeologist claimed to have rediscovered the island in 1960, identifying it with "a sunken land mass known as Kharos Bank, a 10-sq.-mi. area near the island of [[Lemnos]]", listed on British naval charts and located about {{convert|40|ft|m}} below the surface. White building blocks (presumably from Apollo's temple) were said to be visible on the sea floor.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,873343,00.html|title=Philoctetes Was Here|magazine=''TIME'' magazine|date=December 19, 1960}}</ref> The Kharos Bank is mentioned by others as a possible site, but there does not appear to have been further work on it.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Harrison|first=S. J.|title=Sophocles and the Cult of Philoctetes|journal=The Journal of Hellenic Studies|date=1 January 1989|volume=109|pages=173–175|doi=10.2307/632045}} [https://www.jstor.org/stable/632045 JSTOR]</ref>
