[[File:Julia Child's kitchen by Matthew Bisanz.JPG|thumb|right]] [[File:Julia Child's Kitchen - Smithsonian.jpg|thumb|right]] [[File:Julia Child's kitchen 2 by Matthew Bisanz.JPG|thumb|right]] '''Julia Child's kitchen''' is a historic artifact on display on the ground floor of the [[Smithsonian Institution]]'s [[National Museum of American History]]: Kenneth E. Behring Center, located in [[Washington, D.C.]], on the [[National Mall]]. The kitchen is not a replica, but is the actual [[kitchen]] used by noted 20th-century [[cookbook]] author and [[cooking show]] host [[Julia Child]], appearing as the backdrop to several of her [[television show]]s.
==History== Built in Child's home on Irving Street in [[Cambridge, Massachusetts|Cambridge]], [[Massachusetts]] in 1961, the kitchen was designed by her husband, [[Paul Cushing Child]] with 38-inch high countertops, rather than the standard 36-inch height, for her 6-foot-2-inch frame.<ref name="Domenica Marchetti">{{Cite news| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/08/12/AR2009081201187.html| title=In Julia Child's Kitchen, A Lifetime of Stories| author= Domenica Marchetti| work= The Washington Post | date= August 13, 2009| accessdate=Aug 21, 2010 }}</ref> Paul also selected the light blue-green color scheme dominating the kitchen's [[wall panel|panel]]s.
It was the setting for three of her television shows: ''[[In Julia's Kitchen with Master Chefs]]'', ''[[Baking With Julia]],'' and ''[[Julia and Jacques Cooking at Home]]'' with [[Jacques Pépin]]. The kitchen was fully transformed into a functional [[Set construction|set]], with TV-quality lighting, three cameras positioned to catch all angles in the room, and a massive center island with a gas stovetop on one side and an electric stovetop on the other, but leaving the rest of the Childs' appliances alone, including the "wall oven with its squeaking door."<ref>{{Cite book |title=In Julia's Kitchen with Master Chefs |last=Child |first=Julia |year=1995 |publisher=Knopf |isbn=0-679-43896-3 |chapter=Acknowledgments}}</ref> During taping, the kitchen table and chairs were removed and replaced by a cooking island that had a built-in stovetop and food preparation surfaces.<ref name=SIFAQ>[http://americanhistory.si.edu/juliachild/jck/html/faqs.asp Julia Child's Kitchen at the Smithsonion Institution], FAQ.</ref> This kitchen backdrop hosted nearly all of Child's 1990s television series.
In August 2001, representatives of the Smithsonian Institution met with Child in her home, where she agreed to donate her kitchen to the Institution,<ref name=SIFAQ/> where it is now on display. Shortly after Child's 90th birthday, on August 18 and 19, 2002, Child attended the opening of the display of her kitchen.<ref name=SIFAQ/> Her iconic copper pots and pans were on display at [[Copia (museum)|Copia]] in [[Napa, California]], until August 2009 when they were reunited with her kitchen at the National Museum of American History.<ref name="Domenica Marchetti"/>
