{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}} {{Use British English|date=October 2013}} {{infobox book | <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Novels or Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books --> | name = Sherlock Holmes and the Railway Maniac | title_orig = | translator = | image = Sherlock Holmes and the Railway Maniac.jpg | caption = | author = [[Barrie Roberts]] | cover_artist = | country = | language = [[English language|English]] | series = | genre = [[Mystery novels]] | publisher = [[Allison & Busby]] | release_date = 2002 | media_type = Print (paperback) | pages = | isbn = 0-7490-0546-7 | isbn_note = (first paperback edition) | dewey= | congress= | oclc= | preceded_by = | followed_by = }}
'''''Sherlock Holmes and the Railway Maniac''''' is a [[Sherlock Holmes pastiches|Sherlock Holmes pastiche]] [[novel]] by [[Barrie Roberts]] which pits [[Sherlock Holmes]] against an [[Anarchy|anarchist]] who is bombing trains.<ref name="messenger">[http://www.sherlock-holmes.org.uk/pdf/DM217.pdf ''The District Messenger'', no. 217 7 December 2001] the newsletter of the [[Sherlock Holmes#Societies|Sherlock Holmes Society of London]]</ref>
The story involves real life incidents such as the [[Siege of Sidney Street]].<ref name="messenger"/><ref name="torr">[http://www.lagergaard.dk/books/rev/maniac.html ''The Torr'', Spring, 2002] the newsletter of [http://www.scn.org/arts/poorfolk/ The Poor Folk Upon the Moors]</ref>
The events of the novel bookend the original [[Sir Arthur Conan Doyle|Doyle]] story ''[[His Last Bow (story)|His Last Bow]]''.<ref>[https://www.amazon.com/Sherlock-Holmes-Railway-Maniac-Roberts/dp/0749005467 ''Sherlock Holmes and the Railway Maniac''] at [[Amazon.com]]</ref>
==Reception==
Eric Monahan called the book a "first rate pastiche"<ref name="torr"/> while Roger Johnson stated that Roberts "captures the Watson-Doyle style better than most".<ref name="messenger"/>
